    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u help me understand how a force majeure clause works if there is a sudden regional power grid failure? like if the supplier cant deliver because the power went out for everyone in that area, does that count as an unforeseeable event under most standard contracts?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A force majeure clause, also known as a \"superior force\" clause, is a provision in contracts that excuses parties from performing their obligations when an unforeseen event occurs, such as a regional power grid failure. In general, a force majeure clause requires that the event be:\n\n1. Sudden and unexpected\n2. Beyond the control of the parties involved\n3. Not reasonably preventable\n\nIn the case of a regional power grid failure, it's likely that the event would be considered unforeseen and beyond the control of the supplier. However, the specific circumstances of the event would need to be evaluated on a case-by-case basis.\n\nFor example, if the power grid failure was caused by a natural disaster, such as a hurricane or earthquake, it would be more likely to be considered a force majeure event. On the other hand, if the power grid failure was caused by a maintenance issue or a deliberate act, it may not be considered a force majeure event.\n\nIt's also worth noting that the definition of a force majeure event can vary depending on the jurisdiction and the specific contract. In some cases, the event may need to be \"sudden\" and \"unexpected\" to qualify as",
      "source": "target",
