    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if the supplier says it was just \"unforeseeable chaos\" or some kind of random glitch they couldn't predict, how do we prove it actually meets the legal standard and isn't just them being unprepared? like where is the line between a real force majeure and just bad planning?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When a supplier invokes a force majeure clause, it's essential to scrutinize their claim carefully. To prove that the event was indeed a force majeure, you'll need to demonstrate that it met the three criteria: sudden and unexpected, beyond the control of the parties, and not reasonably preventable.\n\nIn the case of the supplier claiming it was \"unforeseeable chaos\" or a random glitch, you may want to ask them to provide more specific details about the event. Did they have any prior knowledge or warnings about the potential for a power grid failure in the region? Were there any maintenance issues or upgrades planned that could have potentially prevented the failure?\n\nYou can also request documentation, such as records of the power grid failure, witness statements, or expert opinions, to support their claim. Additionally, you may want to review the supplier's internal procedures and emergency protocols to see if they had adequate measures in place to prevent or mitigate the failure.\n\nIt's also worth noting that a force majeure clause typically requires that the event be \"sudden and unexpected.\" If the supplier can demonstrate that they had prior knowledge or warnings about the potential for a power grid failure, it may not be considered a force majeure event.",
      "source": "target",
